        <h2>{{ toc[4].title }}</h2>
        <p>I'm going to end today with one of my favourite things on the internet: a <span data-annotate data-ann-color="var(--emphasis)">website that runs entirely off solar energy</span>.</p>
        <figure>
            {% image "images/low-tech.png", "", "(min-width: 30em) 600px, 100vw" %}
            <figcaption>The solar-powered homepage of {% ext "https://solar.lowtechmagazine.com/" %}Low Tech Magazine{% endext %}</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Rather than running off a green hosting service, they deliver their website to the entire world using a single {% ext "https://homebrewserver.club/low-tech-website-howto.html#server" %}tiny computer{% endext %} powered by a 20 watt solar panel connected to a small battery. The background of the website actually shows the battery level! When the battery is drained entirely, the website will go offline - but it's up 95% of the time ({% ext "https://www.notechmagazine.com/2021/04/solar-powered-website-uptime-for-2020.html" %}a little more in summer, a little less in winter{% endext %}).</p>
        <div class="callout warning">
        <p>This is made possible in part by keeping their average page weight low - they report an average of 0.5MB per page - by delivering their pages without a database, without custom fonts, and using an old-timey image compression technique called 'dithering'.</p>
        <figure class="callout">
            <div class="flex">
                {% image "images/decathalon.jpeg", "Image of a pole vaulter in full colour and resolution", "(min-width: 30em) 300px, 100vw", "Â© Marie-Lan Nguyen/Wikimedia Commons" %}
                <img alt="Image of pole vaulter in greyscale, made grainy by dithering" title="Â© Marie-Lan Nguyen/Wikimedia Commons" loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="/images/decathalon-dithered.png" width="300" height="449">
            </div>
            <figcaption><p>Full disclosure, when I initially dithered this image using {% ext "https://imagemagick.org/index.php" %}the ImageMagick <abbr title="command line interface">CLI</abbr>{% endext %} on my computer, the file-size, counter-interuitively, got about five times bigger. Turns out dithering only reduces file sizes in a "lossless" compression image format (like <abbr title="portable network graphic">PNG</abbr>, as opposed to a lossy format like <abbr title="Joint Photographic Experts Group">JPEG</abbr>). But I still can't get the dithered file size smaller than the full-colour, full-resolution versions I generate in modern web image formats {% ext "https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2021/09/modern-image-formats-avif-webp/" %}<abbr title="AOMedia Video 1 Image File Format">AVIF</abbr> and <abbr title="Iâ€¦ don't know actually. I think 'Web Picture'? Can't find a source.">WebP</abbr>{% endext %}. I have so much left to learn about compression!</p></figcaption>
        </figure>
        </div>
        <p>To be perfectly honest, I actually prefer the aesthetics of their bare-bones solar-powered website to their {% ext "https://www.lowtechmagazine.com/" %}regular website{% endext %} - it feels like I'm reading off a calming e-ink screen (which are, themselves, {% ext "https://www.eink.com/benefits.html#:~:text=compared%20with%20the%20same%20size%20LCD%20screen" %}extremely energy efficient!{% endext %}).</p>
        <p>Is it practical for everyone to run their websites off tiny, solar-powered computers in Barcelona? I wish! But it's a great example of the convergence of many small solutions that can reduce the web's carbon emissions.</p>
